00:04:40.700 --> 00:04:44.750
that we're associated with
developed the kind of ethos

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:45.620
that they did.

00:04:45.620 --> 00:04:48.300
And of course, Doug
with The North Face

00:04:48.300 --> 00:04:50.630
and Esprit and Yvon
Chouinard, whom

00:04:50.630 --> 00:04:54.950
I worked for for a
total of 25 years or so,

00:04:54.950 --> 00:04:58.940
they had different
products, but absolutely

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:01.340
a long list of things in common.

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:06.710
In 1993, Doug had already
sold his portion of Esprit,

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:10.890
and I was getting very itchy
as the CEO of Patagonia.

00:05:10.890 --> 00:05:13.010
I felt like I wanted
to do something else,

00:05:13.010 --> 00:05:15.210
but I wasn't quite
sure what it is.

00:05:15.210 --> 00:05:17.570
And then, Doug Tompkins
drifted into my life.

00:05:17.570 --> 00:05:20.810
And he had put more
thought and longer thought

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:24.200
into how might we
commit ourselves

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:27.470
to the things we love in the
third stage of our lives.

00:05:27.470 --> 00:05:33.050
And that ended up forming
family foundations

00:05:33.050 --> 00:05:38.480
and basing ourselves out
of Chile and Argentina

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:42.380
between the United
States, focused

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:45.180
on building these big projects.

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:48.950
So our foundation is
based on five areas.

00:05:48.950 --> 00:05:52.880
Conservation is probably the one
that we're most well known for.

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:56.150
That's the conservation of
landscape and marine systems.

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:59.060
And we'll talk a little
bit about that at the end.

00:05:59.060 --> 00:06:02.210
Restoration-- the
restoration of forest,

00:06:02.210 --> 00:06:06.900
the restoration of grasslands,
the restoration of our minds,

00:06:06.900 --> 00:06:10.670
but also, the restoration
of extirpated species

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:12.720
wherever we're working.

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:14.870
What is missing?

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:16.430
And we're going to
talk a little bit

00:06:16.430 --> 00:06:17.980
about that in a few minutes.

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:20.480
But re-wilding, the
idea of bringing back

00:06:20.480 --> 00:06:24.230
species to those areas
where they had gone missing

00:06:24.230 --> 00:06:27.620
became easily half
of our work today.

00:06:27.620 --> 00:06:29.630
Regenerative
agriculture-- as Doug

00:06:29.630 --> 00:06:32.660
always says, if you don't
get agriculture right,

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:36.380
you can kiss off the
rest because agriculture

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:42.410
is the greatest use
of terrestrial earth.

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:48.800
It is unconventional
ag, toxic to the soils.

00:06:48.800 --> 00:06:51.440
We could talk about erosion
and all sorts of things that

00:06:51.440 --> 00:06:55.280
are happening today and for
the last 100 years in ag,

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:57.230
but we are very active there.

00:06:57.230 --> 00:06:59.970
And finally, activism.

00:06:59.970 --> 00:07:03.270
As Ed Abbey said,
"Sentiment without action

00:07:03.270 --> 00:07:05.430
is the ruin of the soul."

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:09.720
So unlike a lot of
conservation groups,

00:07:09.720 --> 00:07:13.420
we take activism
very, very seriously.

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:15.630
We believe that if
you see something

00:07:15.630 --> 00:07:18.840
that is going and trending
in the wrong direction

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:21.000
toward your values,
that you need

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:23.130
to stand up and shake the tree.

00:07:23.130 --> 00:07:28.130
So finally healthy,
dignified human communities.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:32.960
We have a saying, "economic
development as a consequence

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:35.760
of conservation."

00:07:35.760 --> 00:07:39.380
So where we work, we're
not finished with our work

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:43.100
until local communities,
provincial communities,

00:07:43.100 --> 00:07:46.190
and in some cases, the
national political scene,

00:07:46.190 --> 00:07:50.570
can benefit from the very
things that we're working on.

00:07:50.570 --> 00:07:55.100
And that's very long-term work,
but very satisfying and a must.

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:56.990
So off we went.

00:07:56.990 --> 00:08:00.380
We based ourselves
outside of PumalÃ­n Park.

00:08:00.380 --> 00:08:02.420
This is in 1993.

00:08:02.420 --> 00:08:07.160
Big change from running
Patagonia and swirling

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:08.150
around the world.

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:09.620
And that's where we ended up.

00:08:09.620 --> 00:08:14.050
This is the farm where we were
based when we were working

00:08:14.050 --> 00:08:16.430
on PumalÃ­n.

00:08:16.430 --> 00:08:20.240
And it's a roadless
area, one of two only

00:08:20.240 --> 00:08:23.550
between Fairbanks, Alaska,
and the tip of South America.

00:08:23.550 --> 00:08:26.510
And we were planted in
the middle of one of them.

00:08:26.510 --> 00:08:27.710
Big change.

00:08:27.710 --> 00:08:33.620
Over the ensuing years, we began
to put teams together and build

00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:37.610
a kind of mental
architecture for what

00:08:37.610 --> 00:08:40.669
could happen in these
regions, in terms

00:08:40.669 --> 00:08:44.660
of conservation and working on
the other goals that we have.

00:08:44.660 --> 00:08:47.480
In the ensuing years,
this is what we've done.

00:08:47.480 --> 00:08:54.920
We have 13 national parks and
just over 13 million acres

00:08:54.920 --> 00:08:58.040
that we have put in to
permanent conservation

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.990
in the form of a national park.

00:08:59.990 --> 00:09:01.910
That's what those teams
have been working on.

00:09:01.910 --> 00:09:04.730
We have a team here
in San Francisco.

00:09:04.730 --> 00:09:08.460
We have one in Chile, of
course, and one in Argentina.

00:09:08.460 --> 00:09:10.100
So why national parks?

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:13.160
When we think
about conservation,

00:09:13.160 --> 00:09:14.780
we get asked that
question a lot.

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:17.180
Why didn't we just buy
the land, put a big lock

00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:20.990
on the gate out in front,
and leave it alone?

00:09:20.990 --> 00:09:23.390
And for us, first
of all, we grew up

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:27.080
in the national park system
of the United States,

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:29.570
which is a big part
of our culture.

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:32.870
You don't think about it so
often, but there they are.

00:09:32.870 --> 00:09:35.660
And if you took them away
in the United States,

00:09:35.660 --> 00:09:37.630
you'd find yourself lacking.

00:09:37.630 --> 00:09:41.120
You'd find yourself wanting
them back and defending

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:42.310
those national parks.

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:48.380
They create a kind of
image for a country

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:54.780
that helps define who
we are as a nation.

00:09:54.780 --> 00:09:59.090
But more importantly, we look
at it as a democratic move.

00:09:59.090 --> 00:10:03.230
If we close off this,
the millions of acres

00:10:03.230 --> 00:10:06.740
that we acquired,
and nobody comes in,

00:10:06.740 --> 00:10:09.320
it's like owning a
Picasso and you hang it

00:10:09.320 --> 00:10:10.160
in your living room.

00:10:10.160 --> 00:10:13.280
And you and your family can look
at it and maybe some friends,

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:14.000
but that's it.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:17.270
If you hang it at MoMA,
millions of people

00:10:17.270 --> 00:10:20.030
can see that Picasso every year.

00:10:20.030 --> 00:10:25.970
And that, to us, is essential,
that access, trails,

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:29.610
all the things that go in with
national parks are available.

00:10:29.610 --> 00:10:32.900
So I'm going to take you
on a very, very speedy tour

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:38.930
through three of our parks that
each have a different ecotype.

00:10:38.930 --> 00:10:44.250
So starting, PumalÃ­n, as you
can see the little white box.

00:10:44.250 --> 00:10:49.580
It's on the Pacific
coast in Southern Chile.

00:10:49.580 --> 00:10:52.340
It's the first park
we ever worked on.

00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:55.580
And it goes from
the Andes at the top

00:10:55.580 --> 00:11:02.060
of the Argentine border,
through 800,000 acres of forest,

00:11:02.060 --> 00:11:04.460
and down to the Pacific Ocean.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:08.810
We were famously called the
couple who cut Chile in half

00:11:08.810 --> 00:11:10.670
when we first got going.

00:11:10.670 --> 00:11:13.910
And we were called a
lot of other things,

00:11:13.910 --> 00:11:16.160
too, but I won't go into that.

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:18.680
So this park is just
over a million acres

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:21.190
and just declared
a national park

00:11:21.190 --> 00:11:24.610
in February 27 of this year.

00:11:24.610 --> 00:11:27.810
The alerce trees-- there
are 30% of the last stand

00:11:27.810 --> 00:11:31.110
of alerce trees in this
park, a first cousin

00:11:31.110 --> 00:11:34.230
to the giant sequoias
here in California.

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:35.820
A lot of flora and fauna.

00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:39.240
It's an impenetrable
forest, which has probably

00:11:39.240 --> 00:11:43.110
been a benefit for it because,
otherwise, a lot more of it

00:11:43.110 --> 00:11:45.030
would have been cut.

00:11:45.030 --> 00:11:50.430
It's also just an exquisitely
beautiful, wild place.

00:11:50.430 --> 00:11:55.770
And we have our own volcano
that went off in 2008

00:11:55.770 --> 00:11:59.370
and created tremendous
havoc for us in cleaning it

00:11:59.370 --> 00:12:00.870
up and reforming.

00:12:00.870 --> 00:12:06.480
Architecture in all of our parks
are always connected to place,

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:09.120
so you never go to a
park that we've worked on

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:11.430
and find the same
style of architecture.

00:12:11.430 --> 00:12:14.340
In this case, it's a
Chilotan wooden style

00:12:14.340 --> 00:12:18.900
reflected in bridges,
reflected in everything we do.

00:12:18.900 --> 00:12:23.730
So forests, rain
forests, and now we

00:12:23.730 --> 00:12:27.510
move south to Patagonia
National Park.

00:12:27.510 --> 00:12:32.370
And we actually have one of the
longtime founder-types sitting

00:12:32.370 --> 00:12:35.160
in the back row back there.

00:12:35.160 --> 00:12:38.800
This was started in 2004.

00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:41.100
It goes from the edge
of the northern ice

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:47.330
cap in southern Aysen
and has the Baker River

00:12:47.330 --> 00:12:50.050
as its Western edge.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:52.600
And it's roughly--
well, no, not roughly--

00:12:52.600 --> 00:12:57.310
764,000 acres, much
of which is grassland.

00:12:57.310 --> 00:13:01.690
It's considered to be one of the
biggest grassland restoration

00:13:01.690 --> 00:13:03.580
projects in the
world, but I never

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:05.420
trust those kinds of statements.

00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:08.170
So I just say it's
one of the biggest.

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:09.400
It's beautiful.

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:10.840
It's emblematic.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.240
And it crosses the border--

00:13:13.240 --> 00:13:15.430
it goes to the border.

00:13:15.430 --> 00:13:20.290
And what you're looking out
from the border in this shot

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:23.620
is Patagonia National
Park in Argentina.

00:13:23.620 --> 00:13:26.980
They're not yet contiguous, but
that would be a wonderful dream

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:29.410
to have them touch one another.

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:32.775
Lots of animals there, some
you recognize, some you won't.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:40.780
This little guy is coming
back from having been

00:13:40.780 --> 00:13:43.540
almost extincted from the area.

00:13:43.540 --> 00:13:46.750
So you have all these
little kinds of victories--

00:13:46.750 --> 00:13:49.390
predators like mountain
lions coming back

00:13:49.390 --> 00:13:53.710
once you stop persecuting
them, bird life.

00:13:53.710 --> 00:13:58.300
Everything begins to come
back as you take, in our case,

00:13:58.300 --> 00:14:03.100
50,000 head of livestock
off this former ranch

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:05.050
and take all the
fences out, which

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:08.080
was nearly 500
miles of fence line,

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:13.900
and you see the region begins
to heal itself with lots

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:15.430
of visitors every year.

00:14:15.430 --> 00:14:18.520
And this, too, was just
made a national park

00:14:18.520 --> 00:14:22.270
at the end of
January of this year.

00:14:22.270 --> 00:14:27.070
A lot of wildlife
work in this park.

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:28.540
Pumas are coming back.

00:14:28.540 --> 00:14:31.180
You have a deer nearly extinct.

00:14:31.180 --> 00:14:34.510
And this is a long
story, but I will just

00:14:34.510 --> 00:14:39.190
tell you that I have often
found that the easiest

00:14:39.190 --> 00:14:41.680
thing we've done is
actually acquire the land.

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:45.220
And the minute the ink
is dry on the check,

00:14:45.220 --> 00:14:48.700
projects like this arise,
as they rightfully should,

00:14:48.700 --> 00:14:52.050
and they become the
challenges and headaches

00:14:52.050 --> 00:14:55.960
and you hope a few
successes as you go along

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:58.550
in creating these
big protected areas.

00:14:58.550 --> 00:14:59.860
These are not guns.

00:14:59.860 --> 00:15:03.280
They're dart rifles,
and just to show you

00:15:03.280 --> 00:15:06.040
a little bit about how
much work there is to do,

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:08.470
besides creating just
the infrastructure

00:15:08.470 --> 00:15:10.220
and acquiring the land.

00:15:10.220 --> 00:15:14.750
Another species reintroduction
here up on the border.

00:15:14.750 --> 00:15:18.460
And you can see the architecture
for this park reflects

00:15:18.460 --> 00:15:19.280
Patagonia.

00:15:19.280 --> 00:15:21.040
It's actually an
English-style that

00:15:21.040 --> 00:15:26.770
was settled by the English
who came to Argentina

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:30.490
and built the
railroads in the 1800s.

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:36.190
And of course, any good
park has campgrounds,

00:15:36.190 --> 00:15:39.200
has trails, and so on.

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:41.840
And this is no exception.

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:47.690
This I put in here because
this is an example of activism.

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:49.160
There was a--

00:15:49.160 --> 00:15:51.530
I won't go into the
whole story, but there

00:15:51.530 --> 00:15:56.840
was a move to dam two of Chile's
most pristine and beautiful

00:15:56.840 --> 00:15:57.830
rivers.

00:15:57.830 --> 00:16:00.380
It was an eight-year
fight, millions

00:16:00.380 --> 00:16:05.420
of dollars spent, many, many
NGOs working against it,

00:16:05.420 --> 00:16:09.860
and truly, David and
Goliath, and finally, we won.

00:16:09.860 --> 00:16:11.510
And those rivers run free.

00:16:11.510 --> 00:16:15.230
So activism attached
to conservation, never

00:16:15.230 --> 00:16:18.770
leave it far behind,
in my opinion.

00:16:18.770 --> 00:16:20.780
The third one,
IberÃ¡ National Park,

