1.7 million acres in the
Northeast eastern section

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:29.240
of Argentina, so cross
the border and go north.

00:16:29.240 --> 00:16:33.590
This is wetlands and
savanna grasslands.

00:16:33.590 --> 00:16:36.140
It's hot, subtropical.

00:16:36.140 --> 00:16:40.080
When we first visited there,
got out of the plane and said,

00:16:40.080 --> 00:16:42.230
let's get back in the plane.

00:16:42.230 --> 00:16:43.010
It's too hot here.

00:16:43.010 --> 00:16:45.890
There are bugs, and it's flat.

00:16:45.890 --> 00:16:49.850
And Doug insisted
and came back quietly

00:16:49.850 --> 00:16:53.390
and bought it a month later,
the first piece of property

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:55.640
we started with.

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:57.770
Because this is what he saw--

00:16:57.770 --> 00:16:59.900
I missed it somehow--

00:16:59.900 --> 00:17:05.089
the tremendous biodiversity,
an area that nobody really

00:17:05.089 --> 00:17:07.660
knew that the province had.

00:17:07.660 --> 00:17:11.060
It was sort of
like no man's land.

00:17:11.060 --> 00:17:14.060
And we've come a
long way since 1997.

00:17:14.060 --> 00:17:17.660
And it is now a national park.

00:17:17.660 --> 00:17:20.690
So just some pictures
of what is there,

00:17:20.690 --> 00:17:23.579
but then what is missing?

00:17:23.579 --> 00:17:25.630
Within five years of
having arrived there,

00:17:25.630 --> 00:17:31.930
we began to realize that
species who were missing

00:17:31.930 --> 00:17:33.880
had to be dealt with.

00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:36.340
You had to actively
figure out how

00:17:36.340 --> 00:17:38.810
to bring them back,
which in Latin America

00:17:38.810 --> 00:17:42.610
was really unheard of,
and most of the Americas.

00:17:42.610 --> 00:17:44.230
The jaguars were missing.

00:17:44.230 --> 00:17:45.990
Giant anteaters were missing.

00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:47.490
Tapirs were missing.

00:17:47.490 --> 00:17:50.350
Green-shouldered macaws missing.

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:54.640
And so we committed ourselves
over the last 14 years

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:56.560
to start bringing them back.

00:17:56.560 --> 00:18:01.270
And all of the species
that you just saw

00:18:01.270 --> 00:18:05.230
have been brought back with
the exception of the jaguar.

00:18:05.230 --> 00:18:08.350
We have adult jaguars, but
you can't release them, which

00:18:08.350 --> 00:18:10.450
is another talk altogether.

00:18:10.450 --> 00:18:13.750
But suffice to say, where
there is someone missing,

00:18:13.750 --> 00:18:18.820
we have committed that where
we work, by the time we leave,

00:18:18.820 --> 00:18:20.350
they will be back.

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:23.380
So just a few shots
of what this entails,

00:18:23.380 --> 00:18:26.770
working with the jaguars at
the jaguar breeding center,

00:18:26.770 --> 00:18:28.520
and so on.

00:18:28.520 --> 00:18:32.560
So as we roll out of those
projects, we're still--

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:38.440
we are an ongoing team working
on new projects, one of which

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:40.270
is in marine conservation.

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:43.870
These are the first two
marine national parks

00:18:43.870 --> 00:18:47.960
of Argentina, something we
started just over a year ago.

00:18:47.960 --> 00:18:51.270
So lots to talk about.

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:53.020
But I'm going to leave
it there, because I

00:18:53.020 --> 00:18:58.710
think it's more engaging if
we get a very fast overview

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:02.980
and then start to visit.

00:19:02.980 --> 00:19:05.080
A lot of people ask
us why do we do this.

00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:09.490
We could just buy yachts
and go lay on the beach.

00:19:09.490 --> 00:19:12.040
Well, this is one
of the reasons.

00:19:12.040 --> 00:19:18.730
And this little guy, certainly
top choice, and generations

00:19:18.730 --> 00:19:20.900
of humans in the future.

00:19:20.900 --> 00:19:26.530
We can't imagine that
it's ethical to leave

00:19:26.530 --> 00:19:31.810
for future generations a mess,
which is the course we're on.

00:19:31.810 --> 00:19:35.350
And as Jane Goodall
says, "We are stealing

00:19:35.350 --> 00:19:37.980
from our children's futures."

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:42.790
And so how do we work
against that trend?

00:19:42.790 --> 00:19:46.240
That's really the
question mark upon us.

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:47.993
So thank you.

