00:22:09.376 --> 00:22:11.500
and then, ultimately, what
brought you to Patagonia

00:22:11.500 --> 00:22:14.572
and how you ended
up as the CEO there.

00:22:14.572 --> 00:22:16.030
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Well, I

00:22:16.030 --> 00:22:18.430
was supposed to go to a
girls boarding school.

00:22:18.430 --> 00:22:21.290
And I swore to my
mother I wouldn't go.

00:22:21.290 --> 00:22:23.690
So I went to the local high
school and then realized I

00:22:23.690 --> 00:22:25.240
didn't--

00:22:25.240 --> 00:22:26.130
I don't know.

00:22:26.130 --> 00:22:29.990
Anyway, Yvon was
renting the house next

00:22:29.990 --> 00:22:33.950
to our family's beach house.

00:22:33.950 --> 00:22:37.290
And there were a lot of
climbers around quite a bit.

00:22:37.290 --> 00:22:39.920
I had an older brother who was
sort of in with that crowd.

00:22:39.920 --> 00:22:42.410
And I was 15--

00:22:42.410 --> 00:22:46.670
artists-- and in the
absence of a pull

00:22:46.670 --> 00:22:49.910
toward my own age at
the local high school,

00:22:49.910 --> 00:22:52.250
I started hanging out with them.

00:22:52.250 --> 00:22:56.690
And then, after my
first year in college,

00:22:56.690 --> 00:22:59.990
my mother informed me during
the front end of summer

00:22:59.990 --> 00:23:02.790
that, contrary to
my personal belief,

00:23:02.790 --> 00:23:04.580
she was not my personal banker--

00:23:04.580 --> 00:23:06.170
[CHUCKLING]

00:23:06.170 --> 00:23:08.280
--and that I needed
to get a job.

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:09.390
So I was worried.

00:23:09.390 --> 00:23:11.290
I didn't know how
to do anything.

00:23:11.290 --> 00:23:14.210
And so Yvon all said, why
don't you come work for me?

00:23:14.210 --> 00:23:14.990
So I did.

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:18.170
There were six people there,
just technical rock and ice

00:23:18.170 --> 00:23:20.180
climbing equipment.

00:23:20.180 --> 00:23:23.840
And so we all wore
bathing suits to work.

00:23:23.840 --> 00:23:26.460
And I would peel the
labels off carabiners

00:23:26.460 --> 00:23:29.180
from Germany or package things.

00:23:29.180 --> 00:23:37.790
And then for every summer
after that, it was a default.

00:23:37.790 --> 00:23:40.350
And then, when I
graduated from college,

00:23:40.350 --> 00:23:42.710
I had no idea what
I was going to do.

00:23:42.710 --> 00:23:44.300
And our family is very strict.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.480
The minute that your degree
touches the end of this finger,

00:23:47.480 --> 00:23:49.580
you're on your own.

00:23:49.580 --> 00:23:54.020
There's like a French guillotine
coming down, which was fine.

00:23:54.020 --> 00:23:55.310
We understood that.

00:23:55.310 --> 00:23:58.200
But I had no idea what
I was going to do.

00:23:58.200 --> 00:24:01.850
And so I just started
working for Yvon

00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:07.250
full time, something I've
never regretted, obviously.

00:24:07.250 --> 00:24:09.560
You know, it was
all pretty organic.

00:24:09.560 --> 00:24:14.340
I think it's very different now
when you graduate from college.

00:24:14.340 --> 00:24:16.820
In your studies, you
have a direction.

00:24:16.820 --> 00:24:19.940
You have a-- you're
going somewhere.

00:24:19.940 --> 00:24:23.670
And in our family, you just
needed to go to college.

00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:26.660
Nobody really talked
too much about what

00:24:26.660 --> 00:24:29.720
you needed to do after
that or preparing for that.

00:24:32.260 --> 00:24:36.050
And then, a year--
let's see, I was 22.

00:24:36.050 --> 00:24:38.680
So when I was 23,
Yvon decided, I'd

00:24:38.680 --> 00:24:43.170
like to make some clothing
for climbers, for all of us.

00:24:43.170 --> 00:24:48.060
And that's how it got going
and that's how it is now.

00:24:48.060 --> 00:24:48.695
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:24:48.695 --> 00:24:50.820
And then, what did your
trajectory there look like?

00:24:50.820 --> 00:24:53.462
How did you go from labels off
carabiners to being the CEO?

00:24:53.462 --> 00:24:55.170
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Oh, you know,

00:24:55.170 --> 00:24:59.640
it was so small,
starting at zero.

00:24:59.640 --> 00:25:06.750
And you did everything--
shipper, hand

00:25:06.750 --> 00:25:11.550
labeling our little tiny
early catalogs out to whomever

00:25:11.550 --> 00:25:13.470
had requested one.

00:25:13.470 --> 00:25:18.990
And I like running things.

00:25:18.990 --> 00:25:20.130
I mean, I see that now.

00:25:20.130 --> 00:25:21.690
I don't think I knew it then.

00:25:21.690 --> 00:25:28.160
But I think I just naturally
expanded what I was doing.

00:25:28.160 --> 00:25:33.140
And Yvon loves
working with women.

00:25:33.140 --> 00:25:37.240
He really-- he's very--

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:39.490
I won't say biased
in that direction--

00:25:39.490 --> 00:25:44.530
but he's cognizant of that
and a lot of trust in me

00:25:44.530 --> 00:25:48.520
and also Malinda
Chouinard, his wife.

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:52.240
So if I was given
something to do,

00:25:52.240 --> 00:25:55.000
I would grab onto it and I
wouldn't-- it's like a bone

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:56.380
for a dog.

00:25:56.380 --> 00:25:58.940
I grabbed it and I
didn't give it back.

00:25:58.940 --> 00:26:00.660
Maybe that's how.

00:26:00.660 --> 00:26:01.690
But I loved it.

00:26:01.690 --> 00:26:08.170
And I have a kind of
endless pit for taking

00:26:08.170 --> 00:26:10.800
on stuff that's
especially difficult

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:14.642
or things that I didn't
know about heretofore.

00:26:14.642 --> 00:26:16.192
SPEAKER: Yeah, yeah, absolutely.

00:26:16.192 --> 00:26:18.650
And one thing I was particularly
curious to ask you about--

00:26:18.650 --> 00:26:21.730
for me, I am such an admirer
and I'm sure many other people

00:26:21.730 --> 00:26:24.400
in the room of Patagonia's
commitment to sustainability

00:26:24.400 --> 00:26:26.842
and how that seems
like it's such a--

00:26:26.842 --> 00:26:27.467
[CLEARS THROAT]

00:26:27.467 --> 00:26:31.270
--excuse me-- core value of the
company through the products,

00:26:31.270 --> 00:26:34.360
through a lot of the campaigns
the company has funded.

00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:37.677
I'd love to hear you talk more
about how that ethos began

00:26:37.677 --> 00:26:40.010
and how you guys really saw
that as tied to the business

00:26:40.010 --> 00:26:42.011
because it seems like it
really always has been.

00:26:42.011 --> 00:26:43.968
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS:
Oh, it's absolutely

00:26:43.968 --> 00:26:45.790
Yvon and Melinda Chouinard.

00:26:45.790 --> 00:26:47.770
Absolutely.

00:26:47.770 --> 00:26:51.460
If you pull a string
in anything that you

00:26:51.460 --> 00:26:53.800
would find inside
the company today,

00:26:53.800 --> 00:26:55.780
that string will lead
back to one of them,

00:26:55.780 --> 00:26:59.560
whether it's child care
and Malinda's insistence

00:26:59.560 --> 00:27:06.260
that we build that
population into our planning.

00:27:06.260 --> 00:27:10.450
The understanding of
the ecological crisis

00:27:10.450 --> 00:27:15.190
in the mid '70s, absolutely,
they both were there at a time

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:16.450
when I had no idea.

00:27:19.810 --> 00:27:23.430
Rose Marcario, the
CEO of Patagonia,

00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:28.660
is absolutely imbued and
very, very aggressive

00:27:28.660 --> 00:27:31.810
about the company taking
a lead, whether it's

00:27:31.810 --> 00:27:37.210
sustainability, or fighting
