So you talked a little
bit in your introduction

00:29:07.550 --> 00:29:11.180
about how meeting Doug Tompkins
had this big influence on you

00:29:11.180 --> 00:29:12.780
and the next phase
in your career.

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:14.738
I would love to hear you
talk a little bit more

00:29:14.738 --> 00:29:16.610
about that-- about
how you guys connected

00:29:16.610 --> 00:29:18.830
and sort of what led you
to make this transition

00:29:18.830 --> 00:29:19.730
into conservation.

00:29:19.730 --> 00:29:22.230
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS:
I'll tell you part of the story.

00:29:22.230 --> 00:29:23.021
SPEAKER: All right.

00:29:23.021 --> 00:29:23.832
[LAUGHING]

00:29:23.832 --> 00:29:26.040
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS:
I met Doug when I was 19.

00:29:26.040 --> 00:29:28.940
He was a climbing partner and
a very good friend of Yvon's.

00:29:28.940 --> 00:29:34.490
And he was a climbing partner
of my former husband's, as well.

00:29:34.490 --> 00:29:40.250
So the climbing community
is kind of small.

00:29:40.250 --> 00:29:43.220
Certainly back then,
it was a lot smaller.

00:29:43.220 --> 00:29:47.630
And I knew him since
I was 19 and knew him

00:29:47.630 --> 00:29:51.040
during the Esprit days.

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:53.900
And then, we sort of
lost track of each other.

00:29:53.900 --> 00:29:57.830
And then, I was down
in southern Argentina

00:29:57.830 --> 00:30:00.950
with Yvon and a few other
people eating dinner

00:30:00.950 --> 00:30:06.470
in this three dog town and
in walks Doug Tompkins.

00:30:06.470 --> 00:30:11.560
And that's where it started,
so it would have been 1990,

00:30:11.560 --> 00:30:12.730
I think.

00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:16.170
And then, it was
like an algae bloom.

00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:17.010
[CHUCKLING]

00:30:17.010 --> 00:30:18.040
SPEAKER: And was he--

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:20.310
were either of you already
working in conservation

00:30:20.310 --> 00:30:22.022
or was it just really
an extension of--

00:30:22.022 --> 00:30:23.730
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: So yeah, Doug

00:30:23.730 --> 00:30:26.810
was looking at the first
piece of property--

00:30:26.810 --> 00:30:28.019
SPEAKER: OK.

00:30:28.019 --> 00:30:29.560
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: --second.

00:30:29.560 --> 00:30:31.470
Yeah, so he was on his way--

00:30:31.470 --> 00:30:32.640
SPEAKER: Yeah, and what--

00:30:32.640 --> 00:30:33.630
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: --in Argentina.

00:30:33.630 --> 00:30:35.880
SPEAKER: Yeah, and what made
you decide at that moment

00:30:35.880 --> 00:30:38.589
that you wanted to make this
shift from having impact

00:30:38.589 --> 00:30:40.380
in the business world
through having impact

00:30:40.380 --> 00:30:41.700
through your new work?

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:42.480
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Oh, well, love

00:30:42.480 --> 00:30:43.530
had a lot to do with it--

00:30:43.530 --> 00:30:44.326
SPEAKER: Yeah?

00:30:44.326 --> 00:30:45.950
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: --you know.

00:30:45.950 --> 00:30:47.820
If everything is built
on that kind of love,

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:49.260
then we'd be in great shape.

00:30:49.260 --> 00:30:52.330
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:30:52.330 --> 00:30:53.800
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Timing.

00:30:53.800 --> 00:31:00.010
I think timing in life is really
40% of what happens to you,

00:31:00.010 --> 00:31:00.730
good and bad.

00:31:03.410 --> 00:31:05.320
We sort of got
together at a time

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:08.860
when I really wanted
to do something else.

00:31:08.860 --> 00:31:11.950
I had started working with
Yvon when I was so young.

00:31:11.950 --> 00:31:13.450
And I was 40 years old.

00:31:13.450 --> 00:31:15.340
And I began to panic
that I would be there

00:31:15.340 --> 00:31:17.950
when I'm 50 and
60, maybe even 70,

00:31:17.950 --> 00:31:21.240
which is where I'm headed now.

00:31:21.240 --> 00:31:24.280
And I didn't know
what it would be,

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:27.070
but I also thought
that the company would

00:31:27.070 --> 00:31:29.540
benefit from new leadership.

00:31:32.400 --> 00:31:36.510
And so the timing
was perfect, really.

00:31:36.510 --> 00:31:38.647
That's how it happened.

00:31:38.647 --> 00:31:40.230
SPEAKER: And obviously,
you've already

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:42.660
shared with us a little
bit about the huge impact

00:31:42.660 --> 00:31:45.369
that you guys have made through
conservation and your work.

00:31:45.369 --> 00:31:47.910
I was curious to hear you just
talk a little bit about what's

00:31:47.910 --> 00:31:49.840
your feeling about
the status of land

00:31:49.840 --> 00:31:51.780
conservation in general today?

00:31:51.780 --> 00:31:54.770
How are we doing?

00:31:54.770 --> 00:31:56.791
Are we doing enough
quickly enough?

00:31:59.642 --> 00:32:01.850
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS:
Well, the obvious answer,

00:32:01.850 --> 00:32:04.656
are we doing enough,
using the royal we--

00:32:04.656 --> 00:32:06.530
SPEAKER: Yeah, right,
exactly-- collectively.

00:32:06.530 --> 00:32:09.170
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Collectively no.

00:32:09.170 --> 00:32:16.370
I think, if you look at
just the raw numbers of area

00:32:16.370 --> 00:32:25.670
protected or even in transition
versus the conversion

00:32:25.670 --> 00:32:28.430
of the natural
world to production,

00:32:28.430 --> 00:32:31.850
we're definitely
on the losing team.

00:32:31.850 --> 00:32:37.770
So I think that to use a
terrible militaristic metaphor,

00:32:37.770 --> 00:32:40.190
there is an army
out there of people

00:32:40.190 --> 00:32:46.780
who don't want to see the
effects of climate change play

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:48.280
all the way out.

00:32:48.280 --> 00:32:53.680
There are millions of people out
there who really still believe

00:32:53.680 --> 00:32:59.140
that development has to be
in balance with conservation,

00:32:59.140 --> 00:33:01.980
however that takes place.

00:33:01.980 --> 00:33:08.630
And no, we're not
moving fast enough.

00:33:08.630 --> 00:33:11.600
We can look at these numbers
that Tompkins Conservation may

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:13.580
be involved in,
but when you look

00:33:13.580 --> 00:33:20.420
at the tsunami that's coming
in, then it feels quite small.

00:33:20.420 --> 00:33:22.130
Yeah.

00:33:22.130 --> 00:33:23.930
SPEAKER: And can you
talk a little bit more

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:25.429
about how you guys
ended up choosing

00:33:25.429 --> 00:33:30.306
Latin America as your
focus area for your work?

00:33:30.306 --> 00:33:32.680
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS:
Really, it started with Doug.

00:33:32.680 --> 00:33:35.590
He was a ski racer, as I was.

00:33:35.590 --> 00:33:40.060
And he used to train in
the off-seasons in Chile

00:33:40.060 --> 00:33:44.230
and Argentina, as all the
teams did in those days.

00:33:44.230 --> 00:33:47.320
And he had no money, so he
would hitchhike around Chile

00:33:47.320 --> 00:33:49.270
and Argentina every season.

00:33:49.270 --> 00:33:52.910
And that's how he began
to know the countries.

00:33:52.910 --> 00:33:55.000
And he really fell
in love with them.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:00.160
And then, in 1968, he talked
Yvon in, in two weeks,

00:34:00.160 --> 00:34:03.520
to drive from San Francisco
to the tip of South

00:34:03.520 --> 00:34:08.530
America surfing, climbing,
skiing off of volcanoes,

00:34:08.530 --> 00:34:12.460
and with the goal of climbing
this emblematic peak called

00:34:12.460 --> 00:34:15.670
Fitz Roy in southern Argentina.

00:34:15.670 --> 00:34:16.360
And they did.

00:34:16.360 --> 00:34:18.790
And they were gone six months.

00:34:18.790 --> 00:34:21.550
And they did everything
they had planned to do.

00:34:21.550 --> 00:34:24.100
And when it was all
over, they sold the van

00:34:24.100 --> 00:34:29.469
they'd driven down in and
came back to California.

00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:33.489
And it really set
something in their minds

00:34:33.489 --> 00:34:37.600
about this place, which
in 1968 was really

00:34:37.600 --> 00:34:46.480
kind of like a phantom, this
romantic, wild place on earth

00:34:46.480 --> 00:34:49.060
that nobody really
knew anything about.

00:34:49.060 --> 00:34:51.219
And then, Yvon,
five years later,

00:34:51.219 --> 00:34:53.830
decides he wants to
start making clothes

00:34:53.830 --> 00:34:58.120
and he settled on
Patagonia as the name.

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:05.530
So when Doug started looking
around to see where he would

00:35:05.530 --> 00:35:07.330
work, at least
one of the areas--

00:35:07.330 --> 00:35:09.274
because at the same time
we're doing all this,

00:35:09.274 --> 00:35:10.690
we're doing other
things, as well,

00:35:10.690 --> 00:35:13.420
that aren't necessarily
directed at the Southern Cone.

00:35:13.420 --> 00:35:18.130
But the conservation side, he
just always had this affinity

00:35:18.130 --> 00:35:20.470
toward it since he got started.

00:35:20.470 --> 00:35:21.940
So that's really the nut of it.

00:35:21.940 --> 00:35:23.790
SPEAKER: Well, that makes sense.

00:35:23.790 --> 00:35:26.950
And of course, we talked about
the incredible announcement

00:35:26.950 --> 00:35:29.659
in January of the
10 million acres.

00:35:29.659 --> 00:35:32.200
And you started to say a little
bit about marine conservation

00:35:32.200 --> 00:35:33.329
is sort of a next frontier.

00:35:33.329 --> 00:35:34.870
I'd love to hear
you talk about where

00:35:34.870 --> 00:35:35.860
do you want to go from here.

00:35:35.860 --> 00:35:37.485
I know you've already
achieved so much.

00:35:37.485 --> 00:35:38.902
But what's sort
of on the horizon?

00:35:38.902 --> 00:35:40.443
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Well, I'm

00:35:40.443 --> 00:35:43.120
definitely interested in
marine protected areas.

00:35:43.120 --> 00:35:49.420
And I don't really see us
moving out of the Southern Cone.

00:35:49.420 --> 00:35:50.500
That's for one thing.

00:35:50.500 --> 00:35:53.530
Because we're a small team.

00:35:53.530 --> 00:35:57.100
And I feel like it's really
important that we build off

00:35:57.100 --> 00:35:59.920
of what we've done so far and
not just go to some new place

00:35:59.920 --> 00:36:02.440
and start from zero again,
because there's still

00:36:02.440 --> 00:36:05.200
so many things that we
could do in conjunction

00:36:05.200 --> 00:36:09.340
with the various governments,
and the two countries,

00:36:09.340 --> 00:36:13.490
and building off of those
relationships, and so on.

00:36:13.490 --> 00:36:18.130
So the marine area,
our big vision

00:36:18.130 --> 00:36:21.180
is going around Cape Horn.

00:36:21.180 --> 00:36:22.790
It is one of--

00:36:22.790 --> 00:36:25.000
it's a convergence,
a marine convergence,

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.640
between the Pacific Ocean
and the Atlantic Ocean.

00:36:27.640 --> 00:36:33.910
So that's where we're
especially interested.

00:36:33.910 --> 00:36:36.340
You know, these are just ideas.

00:36:36.340 --> 00:36:39.310
There are a lot of people
working in the marine area

00:36:39.310 --> 00:36:44.300
down in Chile, not
so much in Argentina.

00:36:44.300 --> 00:36:47.140
I think that it's
important to talk

00:36:47.140 --> 00:36:52.180
with the leaders of the
sovereign states and ask them,

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:55.930
are there areas
where we might be

00:36:55.930 --> 00:37:00.550
of service to the goals of
the government and so on?

00:37:00.550 --> 00:37:02.590
And then, of course,
there are always

00:37:02.590 --> 00:37:06.190
projects that are on
the terrestrial side

00:37:06.190 --> 00:37:09.940
and the agricultural side.

00:37:09.940 --> 00:37:11.680
Although, that's a little--

00:37:11.680 --> 00:37:14.530
that takes place out
of our family life

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:16.880
and not inside the foundations.

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:20.320
So I don't have any
intention of doing

00:37:20.320 --> 00:37:23.260
anything else until I fly away.

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:29.080
So I feel blessed to be
doing what we're doing,

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:33.670
especially blessed that
we have the teams we have.

00:37:33.670 --> 00:37:36.370
I know many times, it's sort
of the Doug and Kris show,

00:37:36.370 --> 00:37:38.680
but that isn't it at all.

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:41.980
We have so many people who've
been with us for so many years.

00:37:41.980 --> 00:37:45.460
And in Chile, these parks
have been built and created

00:37:45.460 --> 00:37:46.340
by Chileans.

00:37:46.340 --> 00:37:49.580
And the same can be said
for those in Argentina.

00:37:49.580 --> 00:37:52.240
So I always need
to remind people

00:37:52.240 --> 00:37:54.880
that we wouldn't have
gotten off first base

00:37:54.880 --> 00:37:58.540
without a tremendous amount
of work and dedication

00:37:58.540 --> 00:37:59.740
on that side.

00:37:59.740 --> 00:38:02.560
And I think that, as
far as we've seen,

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:05.410
we're all in to keep going.

00:38:05.410 --> 00:38:07.630
SPEAKER: That's so wonderful.

00:38:07.630 --> 00:38:08.670
So I know you--

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:11.330
I really like the title that
you gave your talk today

00:38:11.330 --> 00:38:12.610
of paying rent to the earth.

00:38:12.610 --> 00:38:14.680
So I was so curious to hear you
talk a little bit about what

00:38:14.680 --> 00:38:17.070
does that mean to you and
how does that relate the work

00:38:17.070 --> 00:38:17.570
that you do.

00:38:17.570 --> 00:38:19.028
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: I don't

00:38:19.028 --> 00:38:22.180
know who coined that pay your
rent for living on the planet.

00:38:22.180 --> 00:38:25.030
I don't know if it was
Yvon or Doug or both or--

00:38:25.030 --> 00:38:26.170
I'm not sure.

00:38:26.170 --> 00:38:27.580
But it's absolutely true.

00:38:27.580 --> 00:38:32.420
I think, regardless of
where you are in your life,

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:36.830
you're working at Google,
you're working at Patagonia,

00:38:36.830 --> 00:38:41.000
you're working for yourself,
you're not working at all,

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:43.260
it's impossible--

00:38:43.260 --> 00:38:47.000
one of the reasons
we're stuck where we are

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:53.090
is that we, as humans,
have separated ourselves

00:38:53.090 --> 00:38:58.170
from the fact that we're
dependent on the natural world.

00:38:58.170 --> 00:39:02.780
So I think that
the big challenge

00:39:02.780 --> 00:39:07.370
is, how do you use every
asset of your personal life

00:39:07.370 --> 00:39:11.120
toward changing that trend?

00:39:11.120 --> 00:39:12.380
That's really the question.

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:13.190
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:39:13.190 --> 00:39:15.398
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS:
And so when I say assets,

00:39:15.398 --> 00:39:18.350
I think where you
work is an asset, what

00:39:18.350 --> 00:39:23.540
your personal strengths
are are your assets, how

00:39:23.540 --> 00:39:29.220
you use your spare time
is an asset that you have.

00:39:29.220 --> 00:39:33.830
And I think paying your rent
for living on the planet

00:39:33.830 --> 00:39:34.970
is a very--

00:39:34.970 --> 00:39:39.200
it sounds superficial, but
it's actually quite deep

00:39:39.200 --> 00:39:41.110
if you adopt it--

00:39:41.110 --> 00:39:45.080
that I will do
something every day

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:48.160
that has nothing
to do with myself

00:39:48.160 --> 00:39:50.890
and that's how I'm going to
get out of bed every day.

00:39:50.890 --> 00:39:55.430
And it's a slogan in
a certain kind of way,

00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:59.470
but it's an important
one because we

00:39:59.470 --> 00:40:05.680
have to live our lives
with intention to the best

00:40:05.680 --> 00:40:06.610
that we can.

00:40:06.610 --> 00:40:10.030
And it's hard, because we
live in a culture that's

00:40:10.030 --> 00:40:11.650
going in the other direction.

00:40:11.650 --> 00:40:15.880
We're valued by our
financial means.

00:40:15.880 --> 00:40:22.330
The values, the criteria,
by which we're measured

00:40:22.330 --> 00:40:27.080
don't really reinforce pay your
rent for living on the planet.

00:40:27.080 --> 00:40:32.540
So people have to
discard or roll back

00:40:32.540 --> 00:40:34.540
the importance of
some of the criteria

00:40:34.540 --> 00:40:37.000
that we've placed on
ourselves and take

00:40:37.000 --> 00:40:40.600
an independent decision to
live your life differently

00:40:40.600 --> 00:40:44.370
or a little
differently, at least.

00:40:44.370 --> 00:40:45.910
Nobody's a saint here.

00:40:45.910 --> 00:40:49.920
We're all swimming in
this sea of contradictions

00:40:49.920 --> 00:40:52.980
that we face-- climate change
and these other facts that

00:40:52.980 --> 00:40:55.050
are very clear to us.

00:40:55.050 --> 00:41:00.540
And yet, we have tremendous
technology at our touch.

00:41:00.540 --> 00:41:04.440
We have tremendous opportunities
to move around and see

00:41:04.440 --> 00:41:06.990
parts of the world we
wouldn't have otherwise.

00:41:06.990 --> 00:41:12.680
And somehow, we have to find
a real balance between those

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:15.290
things or we're--

00:41:15.290 --> 00:41:19.310
as Jane says, we're
stealing the future

00:41:19.310 --> 00:41:23.100
from those who come after us in
the human and non-human world.

00:41:23.100 --> 00:41:24.240
So that's what it means.

00:41:24.240 --> 00:41:25.940
SPEAKER: Yeah, yeah.

00:41:25.940 --> 00:41:28.530
And you really just
touched upon the value

00:41:28.530 --> 00:41:31.610
of an individual action.

00:41:31.610 --> 00:41:33.744
What advice do you
give people who say,

00:41:33.744 --> 00:41:34.910
I don't know where to start?

00:41:34.910 --> 00:41:36.284
I want to have a
positive impact,

00:41:36.284 --> 00:41:37.990
but I don't know where to begin.

00:41:37.990 --> 00:41:41.660
How do you advise people
to get more engaged?

00:41:41.660 --> 00:41:43.690
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Well, I

00:41:43.690 --> 00:41:45.620
used to speak at a lot
of business schools.

00:41:45.620 --> 00:41:49.420
And always, the day
would end like this--

00:41:49.420 --> 00:41:52.280
what would you do
if you were us?

00:41:52.280 --> 00:41:55.240
And I always say the same thing.

00:41:55.240 --> 00:41:58.900
When I was your age, we didn't
know what we know today,

00:41:58.900 --> 00:42:02.800
so I had it a lot easier
than you guys have.

00:42:02.800 --> 00:42:07.270
The problem is, once
you know what you know,

00:42:07.270 --> 00:42:10.910
then you can't turn
your back on that.

00:42:10.910 --> 00:42:16.950
And so this is a really
simplistic answer

00:42:16.950 --> 00:42:20.040
to your question, but I do
believe that most of life

00:42:20.040 --> 00:42:22.920
is intention.

00:42:22.920 --> 00:42:29.610
It is not difficult to decide
what you personally will do.

00:42:29.610 --> 00:42:33.420
You have to decide that
you're going to do something

00:42:33.420 --> 00:42:37.770
or hopefully plural some things.

00:42:37.770 --> 00:42:42.490
And then, go out and find
out what should you be doing.

00:42:42.490 --> 00:42:44.920
You can make
donations to places.

00:42:44.920 --> 00:42:47.050
And they should be
well-thought through.

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:50.710
Are these groups who are really
active and willing to push

00:42:50.710 --> 00:42:54.040
the boundaries of
what's taking place now?

00:42:54.040 --> 00:42:56.545
Or you can go out
and chain yourself

00:42:56.545 --> 00:43:02.260
to the heavy equipment--

00:43:02.260 --> 00:43:04.270
I don't know what you
call those things--

00:43:04.270 --> 00:43:10.720
and stop big trees from being
plowed down in the Sierra.

00:43:10.720 --> 00:43:12.520
The point is to act.

00:43:12.520 --> 00:43:16.000
The point is to
participate in a way that

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:22.010
reflects your own values all
the time-- not all the time,

00:43:22.010 --> 00:43:24.760
but every day something.

00:43:24.760 --> 00:43:26.020
Because that's the problem.

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:30.190
I think we all get
stuck on, what can I do?

00:43:30.190 --> 00:43:31.700
What should be my first step?

00:43:31.700 --> 00:43:34.180
The first step is just
getting out of bed and saying,

00:43:34.180 --> 00:43:35.790
this is where I'm headed.

00:43:35.790 --> 00:43:40.000
And if I don't know who it is
or where it is or what it is,

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:41.632
I'm going to find out.

00:43:41.632 --> 00:43:43.090
I'm going to try
to figure out what

00:43:43.090 --> 00:43:46.060
are the root causes of where
we find ourselves, which most

00:43:46.060 --> 00:43:49.090
of us are really not clear on.

00:43:49.090 --> 00:43:52.540
And I would include
myself in that category

00:43:52.540 --> 00:43:54.170
several years ago.

00:43:54.170 --> 00:43:56.440
If you don't understand
how we got here,

00:43:56.440 --> 00:43:58.690
you can't really
understand what it

00:43:58.690 --> 00:44:06.610
takes to mitigate those things
that have been so horribly

00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:10.120
destructive in the last
couple hundred years

00:44:10.120 --> 00:44:13.250
or however you
want to measure it.

00:44:13.250 --> 00:44:17.680
I studied the collapse of
civilizations as an avocation

00:44:17.680 --> 00:44:21.250
because I keep trying to
understand, why would we

00:44:21.250 --> 00:44:25.970
do this over and over
and over again, when,

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:30.910
as Jared Diamond would say,
the pattern of civil collapse

00:44:30.910 --> 00:44:34.400
is so repetitive?

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:38.090
So what is it about
us that we can't

00:44:38.090 --> 00:44:40.960
move against those trends?

00:44:40.960 --> 00:44:43.150
Or do we just to
abdicate and say, well,

00:44:43.150 --> 00:44:46.710
this is human nature;
we'll spiral up and out,

00:44:46.710 --> 00:44:49.770
and then evolve again?

00:44:49.770 --> 00:44:52.410
But I say, I don't
think that's--

00:44:52.410 --> 00:44:54.360
I don't think that's
the way to go about it.

00:44:54.360 --> 00:44:58.960
You should try to fight
against those things that

00:44:58.960 --> 00:45:03.340
are triggers for this
toward the destruction

00:45:03.340 --> 00:45:09.550
of the natural world and
the greatest extinction

00:45:09.550 --> 00:45:12.006
crisis in history.

00:45:12.006 --> 00:45:13.630
And especially, when
you start learning

00:45:13.630 --> 00:45:22.860
about the stakes of the marine
systems, it's bloody desperate.

00:45:22.860 --> 00:45:25.200
So that's a choice.

00:45:25.200 --> 00:45:27.410
We have to make a choice.

00:45:27.410 --> 00:45:30.230
And it doesn't mean you
run off and live in a cave,

00:45:30.230 --> 00:45:35.420
but it does mean that you
have to take a stand somewhere

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:39.080
along the trajectory
of our daily lives.

00:45:39.080 --> 00:45:40.400
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:45:40.400 --> 00:45:41.795
That's wonderful advice.

00:45:41.795 --> 00:45:43.740
Well, I know we have
about 10 minutes left.

00:45:43.740 --> 00:45:45.260
And I'm sure people
in the audience

00:45:45.260 --> 00:45:47.460
are eager to ask
Kris their questions.

00:45:47.460 --> 00:45:50.660
So we have a microphone
here in the center aisle,

00:45:50.660 --> 00:45:54.088
so please feel free to come on
up and share your questions.

00:45:58.080 --> 00:45:59.700
AUDIENCE: Hi, Kris.

00:45:59.700 --> 00:46:02.820
thank you so much for coming
and speaking to Google.

00:46:02.820 --> 00:46:06.930
I know that there's
a lot of inspiration

00:46:06.930 --> 00:46:09.840
around the idea of
protecting half of the earth.

00:46:09.840 --> 00:46:11.940
And I wanted to get
your thoughts on that.

00:46:14.640 --> 00:46:16.020
KRISTINE MCDIVITT TOMPKINS: Yes.

00:46:16.020 --> 00:46:20.540
We just met with Dr.
EO Wilson 10 days ago,

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:25.350
who originated the
concept of Half Earth.

00:46:25.350 --> 00:46:28.080
And then there's
nature needs half

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:31.750
and there are various
versions of this.

00:46:31.750 --> 00:46:35.160
So we all get stuck in,
well, OK, then Half Earth,

00:46:35.160 --> 00:46:36.780
so which half?

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:37.980
And how would that happen?

00:46:37.980 --> 00:46:41.160
So we immediately
set up roadblocks,

00:46:41.160 --> 00:46:44.130
because it would be insanely
difficult to do that.

00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:48.240
However, I think what he's
trying to say and move toward

00:46:48.240 --> 00:46:49.560
is this--

00:46:49.560 --> 00:46:56.260
that for healthy ecosystems
for human and non-human life,

00:46:56.260 --> 00:47:00.760
as a rough estimate,
half of the earth

00:47:00.760 --> 00:47:08.930
needs to be very well cared
for, maybe not completely

00:47:08.930 --> 00:47:10.670
without some production
in it, but it

00:47:10.670 --> 00:47:14.990
has to be really managed, or
systems begin to collapse,

00:47:14.990 --> 00:47:19.140
as they are in the
oceans and so on.

00:47:19.140 --> 00:47:27.340
So I think that it's a bold
way to describe the necessity

00:47:27.340 --> 00:47:30.700
to move forward from
where we are now to where

00:47:30.700 --> 00:47:33.820
we need to get to in 50 years.

00:47:33.820 --> 00:47:36.490
What should we look like
at the end of this century?

00:47:36.490 --> 00:47:40.610
I think, for me, it's a
better way to look at this.

00:47:40.610 --> 00:47:43.490
And when you have a
circumstance where

00:47:43.490 --> 00:47:45.950
you have rising human
population base,

00:47:45.950 --> 00:47:48.230
you have a rising
consumption level,

00:47:48.230 --> 00:47:50.480
and you have a
falling resource base,

00:47:50.480 --> 00:47:53.180
so somewhere, if you
just do the math,

00:47:53.180 --> 00:47:56.750
you have this inherent conflict
that we're speeding toward.

00:47:56.750 --> 00:47:58.640
And it has different
manifestations,

00:47:58.640 --> 00:48:01.340
whether it's climate
change or other big moves,

00:48:01.340 --> 00:48:04.590
the extinction
crisis, and so on.

00:48:04.590 --> 00:48:09.950
So I think that, yes, the
conversation of Half Earth

00:48:09.950 --> 00:48:13.660
needs to be on the table.

00:48:13.660 --> 00:48:20.080
How do you execute that and how
do you move just intellectually

00:48:20.080 --> 00:48:23.360
toward that is a challenge.

00:48:23.360 --> 00:48:28.320
It's not simple, but
it's probably real.

00:48:28.320 --> 00:48:30.670
I think it's real.

00:48:30.670 --> 00:48:32.340
And I think that we--

00:48:32.340 --> 00:48:35.430
as these crises begin to
mount, whether they're

00:48:35.430 --> 00:48:38.460
through climate change
and other factors,

00:48:38.460 --> 00:48:41.490
society will move toward
that by necessity.

00:48:41.490 --> 00:48:46.550
So it's not all going to
be volunteer or voluntary,

00:48:46.550 --> 00:48:48.330
but it will be
something like that.

00:48:54.310 --> 00:48:56.090
It's a lot to wrap
your head around.

00:48:56.090 --> 00:49:00.290
It's a lot for me to
wrap around my head.

00:49:00.290 --> 00:49:04.180
But my instincts tell
me that our way of life,

00:49:04.180 --> 00:49:06.730
imagining there are
no limits to growth,

00:49:06.730 --> 00:49:09.130
there are no limits to
the things that we want

00:49:09.130 --> 00:49:16.540
and that we can do, is truly
a fabrication of false hope.

00:49:16.540 --> 00:49:18.260
It's not true.

00:49:18.260 --> 00:49:19.990
I don't believe it.

00:49:19.990 --> 00:49:22.030
I don't think
anybody who's really

00:49:22.030 --> 00:49:26.780
thought about the possibility
of economic growth--

00:49:26.780 --> 00:49:30.350
infinite economic
growth-- is possible.

00:49:30.350 --> 00:49:34.770
And I know there are bazillions
of conversations about this.

00:49:34.770 --> 00:49:38.340
And I don't pretend to
have the final answer.

00:49:38.340 --> 00:49:43.230
But I do know that these
are things that individuals,

00:49:43.230 --> 00:49:47.960
companies, everybody
needs to be talking about,

00:49:47.960 --> 00:49:49.880
instead of sitting
on them as if there's

00:49:49.880 --> 00:49:53.650
some sort of deep secret
that nobody wants to face.

00:49:53.650 --> 00:49:58.023
Then, as in all things, that
will knock you off your chair.

00:50:03.334 --> 00:50:04.750
AUDIENCE: Thanks
for coming today.

00:50:04.750 --> 00:50:06.370
Congrats on 10 million acres.

00:50:06.370 --> 00:50:08.380
That's a big number.

00:50:08.380 --> 00:50:12.640
What do you consider the
essential pieces of that

00:50:12.640 --> 00:50:14.020
really coming to reality?

00:50:14.020 --> 00:50:17.200
And if you had to
counsel groups,

00:50:17.200 --> 00:50:19.060
such as yourselves,
that were getting

00:50:19.060 --> 00:50:21.280
started in other
places in the world,

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:25.240
and things that come to mind
are, how does the president

00:50:25.240 --> 00:50:30.610
balance all the influences
on then business development

00:50:30.610 --> 00:50:34.020
growth with preserving nature?

00:50:34.020 --> 00:50:35.200
What were the hard parts?

00:50:35.200 --> 00:50:36.260
How did you solve them?

00:50:36.260 --> 00:50:38.915
And how would you advise
others in your shoes?

00:50:38.915 --> 00:50:40.540
KRISTINE MCDIVITT
TOMPKINS: Well, first

00:50:40.540 --> 00:50:42.220
of all, which is
the most nebulous,

00:50:42.220 --> 00:50:44.230
and I apologize
for this, but there

00:50:44.230 --> 00:50:47.500
are moments when things
like this at this scale

00:50:47.500 --> 00:50:48.820
can take place.

00:50:48.820 --> 00:50:52.250
And there are other moments
when the stars aren't lined up

00:50:52.250 --> 00:50:56.810
and the circumstances are
not there for you to do it.

00:50:56.810 --> 00:51:00.030
So that's a piece of it.

00:51:00.030 --> 00:51:01.540
And it's not a small piece.

00:51:01.540 --> 00:51:08.550
But as we see, even in the
United States now, leadership

00:51:08.550 --> 00:51:11.730
and how it looks at
conservation protected areas,

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:14.820
whether they're parks or
monuments, and the idea

00:51:14.820 --> 00:51:19.050
of public lands in general,
varies from administration

00:51:19.050 --> 00:51:20.520
to administration.

00:51:20.520 --> 00:51:23.490
So it is a matter of
picking your moment.

00:51:23.490 --> 00:51:27.990
And it is a matter of
really tying the economics

00:51:27.990 --> 00:51:32.400
for the regions that
these parks are located,

00:51:32.400 --> 00:51:36.450
that the economic development
long term is actually

00:51:36.450 --> 00:51:40.900
probably best suited to
be tied to, in this case,

00:51:40.900 --> 00:51:44.470
a national park, and as
I said at the beginning,

00:51:44.470 --> 00:51:48.160
economic development as a
consequence of conservation.

00:51:48.160 --> 00:51:50.050
And a really good
way to look at this

00:51:50.050 --> 00:51:53.650
is if you see the
country of Botswana--

00:51:53.650 --> 00:51:58.330
15 years, 25 years ago, Botswana
had a big kind of vision plan

00:51:58.330 --> 00:51:59.140
for their country.

00:51:59.140 --> 00:52:02.150
And it involved mining
and all sorts of things.

00:52:02.150 --> 00:52:04.990
But then, starting with
the Okavango, of course,

00:52:04.990 --> 00:52:08.980
it began to see that
tourism was changing

00:52:08.980 --> 00:52:13.090
the story for many
local economies

00:52:13.090 --> 00:52:16.600
and it doesn't show
any sign of shrinking.

00:52:16.600 --> 00:52:18.610
In fact, it's growing.

00:52:18.610 --> 00:52:23.110
So we were able to work
with Chilean leadership

00:52:23.110 --> 00:52:28.680
in creating these
parks as a master

00:52:28.680 --> 00:52:31.380
plan for economic development.

00:52:31.380 --> 00:52:35.230
It is not true--

00:52:35.230 --> 00:52:39.120
I don't know of any
case where countries

00:52:39.120 --> 00:52:42.660
who have developed
national parks

00:52:42.660 --> 00:52:46.140
have kicked the bejesus
out of their ability

00:52:46.140 --> 00:52:48.390
to grow economically.

00:52:48.390 --> 00:52:51.060
It is a myth that company--

00:52:51.060 --> 00:52:54.330
excuse me, that's
a Freudian slip--

00:52:54.330 --> 00:52:57.690
countries have to choose
one way or the other.

00:52:57.690 --> 00:53:00.450
It's just not true.

00:53:00.450 --> 00:53:04.670
If I was leading a country,
which I never will,

00:53:04.670 --> 00:53:07.070
you need to do both.

00:53:07.070 --> 00:53:11.270
If you're an
inspired leader, you

00:53:11.270 --> 00:53:16.180
have the courage
to insist on both.

00:53:16.180 --> 00:53:22.300
And this, I think,
was the motivation

00:53:22.300 --> 00:53:25.600
for President Bachelet
because, mark my words,

00:53:25.600 --> 00:53:29.860
anybody can have a great
idea, but you will not achieve

00:53:29.860 --> 00:53:32.200
that great idea unless--

00:53:32.200 --> 00:53:33.910
especially at a large
scale-- unless you

00:53:33.910 --> 00:53:39.820
have true partnerships who
will go the distance with you.

00:53:39.820 --> 00:53:43.300
And in this case, President
Bachelet and her ministers

00:53:43.300 --> 00:53:46.580
were absolutely the
reason this happened.

00:53:46.580 --> 00:53:48.460
I mean, we couldn't
have done it on our own

00:53:48.460 --> 00:53:50.710
because we don't
make national parks.

00:53:50.710 --> 00:53:52.630
We don't designate them, I mean.

00:53:52.630 --> 00:53:55.340
So if somebody wants
to start something,

00:53:55.340 --> 00:54:01.200
whether it's here, wherever
it is, to your question,

00:54:01.200 --> 00:54:04.500
you have to decide what it
is you're trying to save.

00:54:04.500 --> 00:54:06.340
You have to know
that area like crazy.

00:54:06.340 --> 00:54:07.620
You need to map it.

00:54:07.620 --> 00:54:08.880
You need to think about it.

00:54:08.880 --> 00:54:10.200
You need to walk across it.

00:54:10.200 --> 00:54:13.890
You need to know who
your neighbors are.

00:54:13.890 --> 00:54:16.380
You need to know
if the country--

00:54:16.380 --> 00:54:21.140
if this would be an asset
for the country overall.

00:54:21.140 --> 00:54:25.900
It's just like building
any big project.

00:54:25.900 --> 00:54:27.670
You have to do a
lot of groundwork

00:54:27.670 --> 00:54:31.040
first and then take
your first step.

00:54:31.040 --> 00:54:33.670
But before that, you
have to love these areas.

00:54:33.670 --> 00:54:35.690
Whatever it is, you
better love them.

00:54:35.690 --> 00:54:38.770
And it better be a deep love
because these things are not

00:54:38.770 --> 00:54:40.480
simple.

00:54:40.480 --> 00:54:45.970
And you have to be willing to
be unpopular sometimes and hold

00:54:45.970 --> 00:54:48.820
hopes and dreams
for your land trust

00:54:48.820 --> 00:54:52.960
or whatever it is that
will be challenged.

00:54:52.960 --> 00:54:59.720
And people will find you're an
intrusion on the development

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:03.260
of the economy and so on.

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:05.270
So you have to stay the course.

00:55:05.270 --> 00:55:08.997
That's another point
of advice I'd give you.

00:55:08.997 --> 00:55:09.830
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

